nsion provider. This type of personal pension scheme is called &lsquo;defined contribution&rsquo;.</p>\n\n<p>The 3 basic steps when arranging your retirement income are:</p>\n\n<ol class=\"steps\">\n<li><p>Decide when you want to retire.</p>\n</li>\n<li><p>Decide how you want to be paid.</p>\n</li>\n<li><p>Shop around for the best deal on a regular payment (buying an ‘annuity’).</p>\n</li>\n</ol>\n\n<h2>Deciding when to retire</h2>\n\n<p>Generally, the older you are when you take your pension the higher the payments because your life expectancy is shorter.</p>\n\n<h2>Deciding how you want to be paid</h2>\n\n<p>When you&rsquo;re close to retirement you have to decide how you want your pension to be paid. </p>\n\n<p>This will depend on the arrangements you have with your pension provider but usually you&rsquo;ll have the option to get 25% of the money from your pension fund as a lump sum and the rest as regular payments. </p>\n\n<p>These can be monthly, quarterly, half-yearly or annually. </p>\n\n<p>If all your pension funds total £18,000 or less, you can take the whole amount as a lump sum. You have to be at least 60 to do this. </p>\n\n<p>In some cases, when you&rsquo;re under 75 and are expected to live less than a year, you can take your whole fund as a lump sum. You won&rsquo;t have to pay tax on it unless your pension funds are worth more than the <a rel=\"external\" href=\"http://www.hmrc.gov.uk/pensionschemes/understanding-la.htm\" title=\"lifetime tax allowance for pensions\">lifetime allowance.</a></p>\n\n<h2>Arranging regular pension payments</h2>\n<p>In most defined contribution pension schemes you&rsquo;ll have to buy an annuity (a retirement income). This is a contract between you and an insurance company. You hand over all or part of your pension fund to them and they give you regular payments until you die. </p>\n\n<p>The amount of the regular pension payments under your annuity depends on how long the insurance company expects you to live and how many years they&rsquo;ll have to pay you. </p>\n\n<p>To calculate your annuity they could take into account:</p>\n\n<ul>\n  <li>your age </li>\n  <li>your gender </li>\n  <li>the size of your pension fund </li>\n  <li>interest rates </li>\n  <li>sometimes your health </li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>You don&rsquo;t have to buy your annuity from your pension provider. There are different kinds of annuity and you should <a rel=\"external\" href=\"http://www.moneyadviceservice.org.uk/en/articles/how-to-shop-around-for-an-annuity\" title=\"shop around for an annuity\">shop around to get the best deal.</a></p>\n"},{"web_url":"https://www.gov.uk/personal-pensions-your-rights/personal-pensions","slug":"personal-pensions","order":3,"title":"Personal pensions","body":"<p>You can either make monthly or lump sum payments to a pension provider. They will send you annual statements, telling you how much your fund is worth.</p>\n\n<p>The amount you get when you retire depends on how much you paid in, how well the fund’s investments have done and how you decide for your <a href=\"/personal-pensions-your-rights/how-your-pension-is-paid\" title=\"annuity\">retirement income to be paid</a>, eg as lump sums or regular payments.</p>\n\n<p>You can take up to 25% of the fund as a tax-free lump sum if you want to.</p>\n\n<h2>Your employer offers a personal pension</h2>\n<p>If your employer offers a group personal pension as their workplace pension, they usually pay contributions. However, the rules on <a href=\"/workplace-pensions/what-you-your-employer-and-the-government-pay\" title=\"Employer contributions to personal pensions\">how much they have to pay</a> are changing.</p>\n\n<p>If you leave your job or change to another personal pension, the money paid in <a href=\"/workplace-pensions/changing-jobs-and-taking-leave\" title=\"Personal pensions when you change jobs\">stays in your pension pot.</a> </p>\n"},{"web_url":"https://www.gov.uk/personal-pensions-your-rights/stakeholder-pensions","slug":"stakeh