n/personal-and-workplace-pensions\" title=\"When you can get your personal or workplace pension\">you’re seriously ill</a>.</p>\n</div>\n\n<h2>Workplace pensions and the State Pension</h2>\n\n<p>Today the maximum basic State Pension you can get is £107.45 per week for a single person. </p>\n\n<p>The money you get from a workplace or other pension could make it much easier for you financially when you’re retired.</p>\n\n<h2>&lsquo;Automatic enrolment&rsquo;</h2>\n\n<p>A new law means that every employer must automatically enrol workers into a workplace pension scheme if they:</p>\n\n<ul>\n  <li>are aged between 22 and State Pension age</li>\n  <li>earn more than £8,105 a year</li>\n  <li>work in the UK</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>This is called &lsquo;automatic enrolment&rsquo;.</p>\n\n<div class=\"application-notice info-notice\">\n<p>Check if the new law applies to you and when you may be <a href=\"/auto-enrolled-into-workplace-pension\" title=\"Will I be automatically enrolled into a workplace pension?\">enrolled into your employer’s scheme</a>.</p>\n</div>\n\n<p>If you’re already in a workplace pension scheme, you may not see any changes. Your workplace pension scheme will usually carry on as normal. </p>\n\n<p>But if your employer doesn’t make a contribution to your pension now, they will have to by law when they &lsquo;automatically enrol&rsquo; every worker.</p>\n"},{"web_url":"https://www.gov.uk/workplace-pensions/types-of-workplace-pensions","slug":"types-of-workplace-pensions","order":2,"title":"Types of workplace pensions","body":"<p>There are 2 main types of workplace pension. Your employer decides which type of scheme you are offered.</p>\n\n<h2>Defined contribution pension schemes</h2>\n\n<p>These are also known as &lsquo;money purchase&rsquo; schemes.</p>\n\n<p>The money is invested by a pension provider chosen by your employer. The amount you get when you retire usually depends on: </p>\n\n<ul>\n  <li>how much has been paid in</li>\n  <li>how long you&rsquo;ve been paying in</li>\n  <li>how well the investment has done</li>\n</ul>\n\n<div class=\"application-notice help-notice\">\n<p>The value can go up or down in the short term. But pensions usually grow more than savings accounts over the long term.</p>\n</div>\n\n<p>Some schemes gradually move your money into lower-risk investments as you get nearer to retirement age. </p>\n\n<p>If this doesn&rsquo;t happen automatically, you may be able to ask for this to happen - ask your pension provider for more details.</p>\n\n<p>The pension provider usually takes a small percentage of your pension pot as a management fee. Check the documents your employer gives you, or ask them, if you want to know how much this will be.</p>\n\n<h2>Defined benefit pension schemes</h2>\n\n<p>These are also known as &lsquo;final salary&rsquo; or &lsquo;salary-related&rsquo; pensions. They promise to give you a certain amount each year when you retire. This amount is fixed - it doesn&rsquo;t depend on investments. </p>\n\n<p>The amount you&rsquo;ll get depends on your salary and on how long you&rsquo;ve worked for your employer. The pension scheme administrator can give you more details.</p>\n"},{"web_url":"https://www.gov.uk/workplace-pensions/what-you-your-employer-and-the-government-pay","slug":"what-you-your-employer-and-the-government-pay","order":3,"title":"What you, your employer and the government pay","body":"<p>If you pay Income Tax, the government will add money to your workplace pension in the form of <a href=\"/income-tax-reliefs/pension-contributions-tax-relief\" title=\"Pension contributions - tax relief\">tax relief.</a></p>\n\n<p>Many employers also add money too. A new law means that employers must pay in to eligible workers&rsquo; pension schemes. </p>\n\n<div class=\"application-notice info-notice\">\n<p>Check if the new law applies to you and when you may be <a href=\"/auto-enrolled-into-workplace-pension\" title=\"Will I be automatically enrolled into a workplace pension?\">enrolled into your employer’s scheme.</a></p>\n</div>\n\n<h2>Who pays what</h2>\n\n<p>The amount you and your employer pay in varies according to what type of workplace pension scheme you’re in. </p>\n\n<h2>You&rsquo;ve been automatically enrolled in a workplace pension</h2>\n\n<p>The law says a minimum percentage of your &lsquo;qualifying earnings&rsquo; must be paid into your workplace pension scheme. </p>\n\n<p>&lsquo;Qualifying earnings&rsquo; are either:</p>\n\n<ul>\n  <li>the amount you earn before tax between £5,564 and £42,475 a year</li>\n  <li>your entire salary or wages before tax</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>Your employer chooses how to work out your qualifying earnings.</p>\n\n<p>You and your employer can pay in more than the legal minimum. You can pay in less - as long as your employer&rsquo;s contribution means at least the minimum has been paid.</p>\n\n<p>If your employer offers you a <a href=\"/workplace-pensions/types-of-workplace-pensions\" title=\"types of workplace pensions\">defined contribution scheme,</a> the minimum amounts can go up in October 2017 and October 2018.</p>\n\n<p>Most <a href=\"/workplace-pensions/types-of-workplace-pensions\" title=\"types of workplace pensions\">defined benefit schemes</a> pay above the minimum.</p>\n\n<table>\n  <thead>\n    <tr>\n      <th>The minimum you pay</th>\n      <th>The minimum your employer pays</th>\n      <th>The government pays</th>\n    </tr>\n  </thead>\n  <tbody>\n    <tr>\n      <td>0.8% of your &lsquo;qualifying earnings&rsquo; rising to 4% by 2018</td>\n      <td>1% of your &lsquo;qualifying earnings&rsquo; rising to 3% by 2018</td>\n      <td>0.2% of your &lsquo;qualifying earnings&rsquo; rising to 1% by 2018</td>\n    </tr>\n  </tbody>\n</table>\n\n<div class=\"application-notice info-notice\">\n<p>Work out your contributions using the <a href=\"https://www.moneyadviceservice.org.uk/en/tools/workplace-pension-contribution-calculator\" title=\"Workplace Pension Contribution Calculator\" rel=\"external\">Money Advice Service’s contributions calculator.</a></p>\n</div>\n\n<h2>How contributions work</h2>\n\n<p>Your pension pot builds up each payday with your employer&rsquo;s contributions and tax relief. This is how it works if you&rsquo;re in a defined contribution pension scheme.</p>\n\n<p><img src=\"https://assets.digital.cabinet-office.gov.uk/static/workplace_pensions_pots.jpg\" width=\"320\" height=\"260\" alt=\"John puts in £40, his employer puts in £30, the government adds £10 tax relief\" /></p>\n\n<h2>Not yet automatically enrolled into a workplace pension</h2>\n\n<p>Your employer decides the minimum and maximum amounts you and they can pay in. If you pay Income Tax, the government automatically adds <a href=\"/income-tax-reliefs/pension-contributions-tax-relief\" title=\"pension contributions tax relief\">&lsquo;tax relief&rsquo;</a> to your contribution.</p>\n\n<h2>The effect on your tax credits or student loan repayments</h2>\n\n<p>Joining a workplace pension scheme means that your take-home income will be reduced. But this may:</p>\n\n<ul>\n  <li>mean you&rsquo;re entitled to tax credits or increase the amount of tax credits you get</li>\n  <li>reduce the amount of student loan repayments you need to make</li>\n</ul>\n"},{"web_url":"https://www.gov.uk/workplace-pensions/protection-for-your-pension","slug":"protection-for-your-pension","order":4,"title":"Protection for your pension","body":"<p>The money in every pension scheme is protected - how your pension is protected depends on the <a href=\"/workplace-pensions/types-of-workplace-pensions\" title=\"types of pensions\">type of scheme</a>.</p>\n\n<h2>Defined contribution pension schemes</h2>\n\n<h3>Your employer goes bust</h3>\n\n<p>Defined contribution schemes are usually run by pension providers, not employers. If your employer goes bust, you won&rsquo;t lose your pension pot.  </p>\n\n<h3>Your pension provider goes bust</h3>\n\n<p>If the pension provider was authorised by the Financial Services Authority and can&rsquo;t pay, you can get compensation from the <a rel=\"external\" href=\"http://www.fscs.org.uk/\" title=\"Financial Services Compensation Scheme (FSCS)\">Financial Services Compensation Scheme (FSCS).</a></p>\n\n<h3>Trust-based schemes</h3>\n\n<p>Some defined contribution schemes are run by a trust appointed by the employer. These are called &lsquo;trust-based schemes&rsquo;. </p>\n\n<p>If your employer goes out of business, you&rsquo;ll still get your pension. But you might not get as much because the scheme&rsquo;s running costs will be paid by members&rsquo; pension pots instead of the employer.</p>\n\n<h2>Defined benefit pension schemes</h2>\n\n<p>Your employer is responsible for making sure there&rsquo;s enough money in the pension fund to pay each member the promised amount.</p>\n\n<div class=\"application-notice info-notice\">\n<p>If your employer is in financial trouble, they can’t touch the money in your pension.</p>\n</div>\n\n<p>If they go bust and can&rsquo;t pay your pension, you&rsquo;re usually protected by the <a rel=\"external\" href=\"http://www.pensionprotectionfund.org.uk/\" title=\"Pension Protection Fund\">Pension Protection Fund.</a> </p>\n\n<p>The Pension Protection Fund usually pays:</p>\n\n<ul>\n  <li>100% compensation if you&rsquo;ve reached the scheme’s pension age </li>\n  <li>90% compensation if you&rsquo;re below the scheme&rsquo;s pension age</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h2>Fraud, theft or bad management</h2>\n\n<p>If there&rsquo;s a shortfall in your company&rsquo;s pension fund because of fraud or theft, the <a rel=\"external\" href=\"http://www.pensionprotectionfund.org.uk/\" title=\"Pension Protection Fund\">Pension Protection Fund</a>  may be able to recover some of the money.</p>\n\n<p>If you want to make a complaint about the way your workplace pension scheme is run, contact either: </p>\n\n<ul>\n  <li><a rel=\"external\" href=\"http://www.pensionsadvisoryservice.org.uk/dealing-with-complaints\" title=\"Dealing with complai